This now leads me to notice another family of Ferus -namely, Marattiaceae, which have a vet-y distinct and special habit from other Ferus, and are well marked by the sporangia being destitute of a ring. The evolution of the {rond is terminal and articulate to the caudex, as in Gyathew arborea above noticed‚ but differs in the fronds rising from between two stipuliform appendages in the form of a socket‚ analogous to the stipules of phaenogamous plants. The speciality of this group of Ferus leads me to view it as constituting a distinct division, which I have named Scaphobrya.

This division comprehende but a small number of species as compared with Eremobrya and Desmobrya, the number probably not exceeding thirty or forty, the principal part of which are included under the genera Mai-attia, Angri-v opteris and Danaa.
